China 's reform and opening-up policy started from agriculture and rural residents were the first beneficiaries of the policy .
But after 1990s the substantial bias of the economic policies to big cities resulted in the basic standstill of the agrarian reform . The gap between the rural and urban regions was increasingly widened as a result .
As time went on , in China appear two entirely different worlds : one is the highly prosperous cities and the other is the poor and backward countryside .
To quote Chinese officials , the widening gap between the rich cities and the poor countryside is " a problem in the course of development " and it can be solved by sustaining the development .
In other words China 's coastal regions and cities should keep developing and should not be held back by the rural problems .
However , on seeing small changes in one year and big changes in 3 years in large cities , people cannot help asking why few changes have taken place for decades in some poverty-stricken areas .
Of course we have to admit the fact that the rural areas and cities differ in their developing ways , but the problem is , while investing large sums of money in urban construction and in encouraging and backing the rich middle class , whether or not the rural people occupying 70 % of the whole population have enjoyed the same care and attention .
In theory it cannot claim that all the previous Chinese governments have failed to attach importance to agriculture , rural areas and peasants .
But in the past years things have been more and more difficult and have become worse in the countryside . This shows that the attention paid to the countryside is becoming more and more insufficient .
